By Nse Anthony-Uko ABUJA, (Sundiata Post) — The Nigerian economy grew by 0.82 per cent in 2017 compared to a -1.74 per cent contraction in 2016,  further consolidating its recovery from recession, data from the National Bureau of Statistics (NBS) said on Tuesday. This is as the economy recorded a growth of 1.92 per cent in the Gross Domestic Product (GDP) in the fourth quarter of 2017, The GDP Report released on the NBS website on Tuesday also indicated that overall, the econony grew by 0.82 per cent in 2017 compared to a -1.74 per cent contraction in 2016. The GDP grew by 1.92 per cenr in Q4 2017 compared to 1.40 per cent in Q3 2017 and a contraction of -1.73 per cent in Q4 2016.
This means the economy ended 2017 with a growth of 0.82 per cent compared to a contraction of -1.58 per cent in 2016. GDP Growth in the fourth quarter of 2017 was driven by growth in crop production, crude production and natural gas, metal ores, construction, transportation and storage, trade, electricity and gas production. Crop production grew 4.58 per cent in Q4 2017 compared to 3.19 per cent in Q3 2017 and 4.36 per cent in Q4 2016 Crude Production grew 8.38 per cent  in Q4 2017 compared to 25.89 per cent  in Q3 2017 and a contraction of -17.70 in Q4 2016Metal Ore grew 31.86% in Q4 2017 compared to 10.70 per cent in Q3 2017 and 7.03% in Q4 2016. Construction grew 4.14 per cent in Q4 2017 compared to a contraction of -0.46% in Q3 2017 and another contraction of -6.03 per cent in Q4 2016, representing the strongest growth in construction since Q2 2015 Transportation and storage grew 16.57 per cent in Q4 2017 compared to -6.25% in Q3 2017 and -5.32% in Q4 2016 Trade, after 6 quarters of negative growth grew  2.07 per cent in Q4 2017. Electricity and gas production grew 16.03% in Q4 2017 compared to 11.46% in Q3 2017 and a contraction of -5.16 per cent in Q4 2016 Non Oil GDP grew by 1.45% in Q4 2017(strongest growth since 2015) compared to a contraction of -0.76 in Q3 2017 and -0.33 per cent in Q4 2016 Industry grew for the third consecutive quarter (following 8 quarters of negative growth) by 3.92 per cent in Q4 2017 compared to 8.83 per cent in Q3 2017 and a contraction of -8.73 per cent in Q4 2016 Services finally got out of recession, growing positive for the first time since Q1 2016 by 0.10 per cent in Q4 2017 compared to contractions of -2.66% in Q3 2017 and -1.52 per cent  in Q4 2016 